### 8. Exception Handling — `ProcessOrder_EmptyOrder_ThrowsValidationError` (line 110)

```csharp
try {
    processor.ProcessOrder(order);
    Assert.Fail("Expected an exception but none was thrown");
} catch (ValidationException ex) {
    Assert.AreEqual("Order must contain at least one item", ex.Message);
}
```

This is a capture-and-assert pattern (not a swallowed exception), so it's functional but unnecessarily verbose. It also silently swallows any *other* exception type. **Fix:** use `Assert.ThrowsException`:

```csharp
var ex = Assert.ThrowsException<ValidationException>(
    () => processor.ProcessOrder(order));
Assert.AreEqual("Order must contain at least one item", ex.Message);
```

**Risk:** If `ProcessOrder` throws `NullReferenceException` instead of `ValidationException`, the current test fails with an unhandled exception rather than a clear assertion failure.

